   "id": "cf524e9d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# The current LEO population\n",
    "The US government provides GP or general perturbations orbital data for all Earth orbiing satellites as produced from the [US Space Surveillance Network (SSN)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Space_Surveillance_Network). These are in the form of Brouwer mean elements to be used in the SGP4 or [Simplified General Perturbations 4 orbit propagator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simplified_perturbations_models). \n",
    "\n",
    "Together with the Brouwer mean elements, information on the objects [BSTAR](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BSTAR) cefficient is made available and hence on the drag force acting upon it. Some (limited) information on the objects radar cross section (RCS) is also available. \n",
    "\n",
    "Using this data, plausible initial conditions of all the tracked objects can be computed and used to simulte the possible evolutions of the currently known population. In the following, we will see how this can be achieved with Python code. \n",
    "\n",
    "Start with the necessary imports:\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "c9b316b3-8d04-4b55-8395-54be3213bd03",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pykep as pk\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import json\n",
    "import pickle as pkl\n",
    "\n",
    "import sgp4\n",
    "from sgp4.api import Satrec, SatrecArray\n",
    "\n",
    "from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "%matplotlib inline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3a5f6485",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Extracting the data on the currently tracked population\n",
    "\n",
    "We will here make combined use of two files that are distributed by the USSPACECOM. Most of the data contained in the files is derived from observations of the [United States Space Surveillance Network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Space_Surveillance_Network).\n",
    "\n",
    "The files are named:\n",
    "* [satcat.txt](https://celestrak.com/satcat/search.php) downloaded from [celestrack](https://celestrak.com) on January 2022\n",
    "* [satcat.json](https://www.space-track.org/basicspacedata/query/class/gp/decay_date/null-val/epoch/%3Enow-30/orderby/norad_cat_id/format/json) downloaded from [space-track](https://celestrak.com) on January 2022\n",
    "\n",
    "The reason to use both is that, at the time of writing, they contain complementary information. While both contain the tracked objects' Brouwer mean elements and their [BSTAR](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BSTAR), the information on the radar cross section (RCS) is only given for some satellites in the \"old\" satcat.txt. For those objects that do not have such an information, the json file reports, at least, a generic \"SMALL\", \"MEDIUM\", \"LARGE\" category that can be used to assign to the object a dimension (useful in simulations where detected collisions result in break-ups based on the impact energy).\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that the remaining code is written to work with the two files as downloaded in February 2022. We have obtained permission from the SSA Partnership and Coalition Engagement (SPACE) Office (US) to share these, now old, files via the cascade code so that you do not have to download them yorself. In case you do wat to play with the latest versions, you will need a user in the [space-track](https://celestrak.com) website.\n",
    "\n",
    "Lets start importing the files:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "fe16ec86",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Satellites number in satcat (json):  23947\n",
      "Satellites number in satcat_old (txt):  51407\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Import the \"old\" SATCAT\n",
    "satcat_old = pk.util.read_satcat(\"data/satcat.txt\")\n",
    "# Import the json catalogue\n",
    "with open(\"data/satcat.json\", \"r\") as file:\n",
    "    satcat = json.load(file)\n",
    "print(\"Satellites number in satcat (json): \", len(satcat))\n",
    "print(\"Satellites number in satcat_old (txt): \", len(satcat_old))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e3ae6d3d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A different number of objects in the two datsets is expected as the txt (stacat_old) contains also all past decayed objects, while the json file (satcat) contains only the orbiting ones (at the time of download).\n",
    "\n",
    "We then add to the corresponding dictionary an estimate of each object radius in meters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "1942fa6c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of objects with radius estimated from satcat_old:  15941\n",
      "Number of objects with radius estimated from satcat:  8006\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# We add to the JSON entries their estimated radius (key: RADIUS)\n",
    "count = 0\n",
    "for object in satcat:\n",
    "    key = object[\"OBJECT_ID\"]\n",
    "    if key in satcat_old and key !='' and satcat_old[key].radarA.strip() != \"N/A\":\n",
    "        radius = np.sqrt(float(satcat_old[key].radarA)/np.pi)\n",
    "        count+=1\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        if object[\"RCS_SIZE\"] == \"SMALL\":\n",
    "            radius = 0.15\n",
    "        elif object[\"RCS_SIZE\"] == \"MEDIUM\":\n",
    "            radius = 0.55\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            radius = 2.\n",
    "    object[\"RADIUS\"] = radius\n",
    "print(\"Number of objects with radius estimated from satcat_old: \", count)\n",
    "print(\"Number of objects with radius estimated from satcat: \", len(satcat) - count)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "802a50ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to maintain a correspondence between the satcat and the various propagated particles we use, and keep updated, the following array:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "58b4e4b0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of satellites left in the simulation:  23947\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "to_satcat_index = np.arange(len(satcat))\n",
    "print(\"Number of satellites left in the simulation: \", len(to_satcat_index))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d804a028",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "so that, if ```r[j]``` contains the position of an object, ```satcat(to_satcat_index[j])``` will be the corresponding satcat entry. This book keeping is made necessary as objects will be removed for several reasons from the simulation (decayed, exploded, etc..)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ebd17e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are now ready to compute the various object positions at a choosen starting epoch. We will use here the reference epoch 2022-Mar-01 since our files where downloaded at the beginning of 2022. We also use the vectorized version of the SGP4 propagator, hence\n",
    "building first a SatrecArray object (see [sgp4 module documentation](https://pypi.org/project/sgp4/))."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "9dab93b0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# We call the SGP4 propagator to a common initial epoch\n",
    "jd = pk.epoch_from_iso_string(\"20220301T000000\").jd # Julian date corresponding to 2022-Mar-01 00:00:00\n",
    "sgp4_objects_l = []\n",
    "for i, object in enumerate(satcat):\n",
    "    l1 = object[\"TLE_LINE1\"]\n",
    "    l2 = object[\"TLE_LINE2\"]\n",
    "    sgp4_objects_l.append(Satrec.twoline2rv(l1, l2))\n",
    "sgp4_objects = SatrecArray(sgp4_objects_l)\n",
    "err, r, v = sgp4_objects.sgp4(np.array([2459639.5]), np.array([0.]))\n",
    "# Reshaping to remove the middle dimension (its 1 anyway)\n",
    "dims = np.shape(r)\n",
    "r = np.reshape(r, (dims[0],dims[2]))\n",
    "v = np.reshape(v, (dims[0],dims[2]))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea7c600d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Some of the orbiting objects did not make it to 2022-Mar-01 as they have re-entered the Earth atmosphere. Lets count and remove them. First we use the error code from sgp4 to detect decayed  objects:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "e2c4bf01",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of objects decayed:  79\n",
      "Number of satellites in the simulation:  23868\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# We remove the decayed objects\n",
    "mask = np.where(err!=0)[0]\n",
    "for idx in mask[::-1]:\n",
    "    r = np.delete(r, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    v = np.delete(v, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    to_satcat_index = np.delete(to_satcat_index, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "print(\"Number of objects decayed: \", len(mask))\n",
    "print(\"Number of satellites in the simulation: \", len(to_satcat_index))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "af29af05",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And then we filter the objects using their the semimajor axis computed at the epoch ```jd```. This will remove objects that are not LEO as well as those that have been wrongly propgagated by sgp4 well past their decay epoch."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "f5b9564d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of objects removed:  4194\n",
      "Number of satellites in the simulation:  19674\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# We remove other decayed objects computing the orbital elements at jd and filtering again\n",
    "sma, ecc, incl = [], [], []\n",
    "counter=0\n",
    "for pos,vel in zip(r,v):\n",
    "    elements = pk.ic2par(pos*1000,vel*1000,pk.MU_EARTH)\n",
    "    sma.append(elements[0]/1000) \n",
    "    ecc.append(elements[1])\n",
    "    incl.append(elements[2] / np.pi * 180) \n",
    "\n",
    "mask = np.where(np.array(sma)>10000)[0]\n",
    "for idx in mask[::-1]:\n",
    "    r = np.delete(r, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    v = np.delete(v, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    to_satcat_index = np.delete(to_satcat_index, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    sma = np.delete(sma, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    ecc = np.delete(ecc, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "    incl = np.delete(incl, idx, axis=0)\n",
    "print(\"Number of objects removed: \", len(mask))\n",
    "print(\"Number of satellites in the simulation: \", len(to_satcat_index))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0f42b323",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally we detect and remove objects that are co-orbiting, like payloads attached to the International Space Station and similar."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "79d429fc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "Found the following co-orbiting objects:\n",
      "TIANZHOU 2 \t\twith RCS:  2.0\n",
      "TIANZHOU 3 \t\twith RCS:  0.15\n",
      "SZ-13 \t\twith RCS:  2.0\n",
      "\n",
      "Found the following co-orbiting objects:\n",
      "ISS (NAUKA) \t\twith RCS:  2.0\n",
      "SOYUZ MS-19 \t\twith RCS:  0.15\n",
      "PROGRESS MS-18 \t\twith RCS:  2.0\n",
      "DRAGON ENDURANCE \t\twith RCS:  2.0\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# First we find all unique elements in r\n",
    "new_r, idx, count = np.unique(r[:,0], return_index=True, return_counts=True)\n",
    "# We then ask where more than one element occur\n",
    "where = np.where(count>2)[0]\n",
    "# And for each entry that was not unique we retreive what objects\n",
    "not_unique_lists = []\n",
    "for not_unique in where:\n",
    "    not_unique_lists.append(np.where(r[:,0] == r[idx[not_unique],0])[0])\n",
    "# We now print on screen our findings\n",
    "for not_unique in not_unique_lists:\n",
    "    print(\"\\nFound the following co-orbiting objects:\")\n",
    "    for idx in not_unique:\n",
    "        print(satcat[to_satcat_index[idx]][\"OBJECT_NAME\"], \"\\t\\twith RCS: \", satcat[to_satcat_index[idx]][\"RADIUS\"])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "5b6bfafe",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of co-orbiting objects deleted:  5\n",
      "Number of satellites in the simulation:  19669\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# We find all indexes of objects that are not unique (but we keep the biggest)\n",
    "to_delete = []\n",
    "for not_unique in not_unique_lists:\n",
    "    to_delete.extend(sorted(not_unique, key = lambda idx: satcat[to_satcat_index[idx]][\"RADIUS\"], reverse=True)[1:])\n",
    "    \n",
    "# And now we can remove and delete\n",
    "r = np.delete(r, to_delete, axis=0)\n",
    "v = np.delete(v, to_delete, axis=0)\n",
    "to_satcat_index = np.delete(to_satcat_index, to_delete, axis=0)\n",
    "print(\"Number of co-orbiting objects deleted: \", len(to_delete))\n",
    "print(\"Number of satellites in the simulation: \", len(to_satcat_index))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2c84d068",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": []
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1cad14c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## We now produce some plots on the satellites to be simulated\n",
    "At this point, in the simulation, the initial position r[k], corresponds to the entry satcat[to_satcat_index[k]]. Let us plot the distribution and positin of the various objects.\n",
    "First we must compute their orbital elements"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "046849c5-efa7-4fce-8b1b-8244b4879dce",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0.5, 0, 'collision radius')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 900x600 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "radius = []\n",
    "for idx in to_satcat_index:\n",
    "    radius.append(satcat[idx][\"RADIUS\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize = (9,6))\n",
    "axes[0,0].hist(incl, bins=40)\n",
    "axes[0,0].set_xlabel(\"inclination\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1,0].hist(sma, bins=40)\n",
    "axes[1,0].set_xlabel(\"sma\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0,1].hist(ecc, bins=40)\n",
    "axes[0,1].set_xlabel(\"ecc\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1,1].hist(radius, bins=80)\n",
    "axes[1,1].set_xlabel(\"collision radius\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "9b9820ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 700x700 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
    "ax.scatter3D(r[:,0]/pk.EARTH_RADIUS, r[:,1]/pk.EARTH_RADIUS, r[:,2]/pk.EARTH_RADIUS, alpha=0.2, s= 1, c='k')\n",
    "ax.view_init(45,30)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c7520ff0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally we can save all the information into an archive."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "26f4d4e6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "with open(\"data/leo_population.pk\", \"wb\") as file:\n",
    "    pkl.dump((r,v,to_satcat_index,satcat), file)"
   ]
  }
 ],
